{
  "answer": "**Allama Iqbal's *Bang-E-Dara Part 2*, Chapter 23 (\"Swami Ram Tirath\").**[^1]\n\nIqbal praises the Hindu renunciant (sannyasi) Swami Ram Tirath with these two couplets, fusing the Islamic *shahada* (\"La ilaha illallah\": There is no god but Allah) into a pearl-diving metaphor and invoking Abraham (*Ibrahim*) as the iconoclast of the ego (*but-e-hasti*):\n\n> The negation of being is a wonder of the knowing heart;  \n> In the river of 'La' lies hidden the pearl of 'illa-Allah'.[^2]  \n>   \n> The Abraham of Love shatters the idol of the Self;  \n> The remedy for reason is the ecstasy of Love's Tasnim.[^3]\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 2*, Ch. 23 (\"Swami Ram Tirath\"), [translation](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/23-swami-ram-tirath/translation/).\n\n[^2]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 2*, Ch. 23 (\"Swami Ram Tirath\"), [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/23-swami-ram-tirath/translation/#p-ef7cac).\n\n[^3]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 2*, Ch. 23 (\"Swami Ram Tirath\"), [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/23-swami-ram-tirath/translation/#p-7de605).",
